##* {{quote-book|en|author=Mark Sainsbury|authorlink=Mark Sainsbury (philosopher)|chapter=Validity|title=Logical Forms: An Introduction to Philosophical Logic|edition=2nd|location=Oxford, Oxfordshire|publisher=[[w:Wiley-Blackwell|Blackwell Publishing]]|year=2001|section=§&nbsp;8|isbn=978-0-63121-679-7|page=35|passage=Consider the '''argument''': / ''15'') I am hungry; therefore I am hungry. / Intuitively this should count as valid. But suppose we thought of the components of '''arguments''' as sentences, and suppose we imagine the context shifting between the utterance of the premise and the utterance of the conclusion. Suppose you are hungry and utter the premise, and I am not hungry and utter the conclusion. Then we would have a true premise and a false conclusion, so the '''argument''' would not be valid. Clearly we need to avoid such problems, and introducing the notion of a proposition, in the style of this section, is one way of doing so.}}
##* {{quote-web|en|author=Edwin Mares|title=Propositional Functions|work={{w|Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy}}|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200807003134/https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/fall2011/entries/propositional-function/|archivedate=7 August 2020|edition=fall 2011|date=20 July 2011|passage=In ‘The Critic of Arguments’ (1892), [[w:Charles Sanders Peirce|[Charles Sanders] Peirce]] adopts a notion that is even closer to that of a propositional function. There he develops the concept of the ‘rhema’. He says the rhema is like a relative term, but it is not a term. It contains a copula, that is, when joined to the correct number of '''arguments''' it produces an assertion. For example, ‘__ is bought by __ from __ for __’ is a four-place rhema. Applying it to four objects ''a'', ''b'', ''c'', and ''d'' produces the assertion that ''a'' is bought by ''b'' from ''c'' for ''d''{{nb...|}}.}}
